### Step 3: infer and check R data types

Raw extracts arrive with everything as character or numeric, and the wrong type
quietly breaks an analysis: an ID read as a number gets averaged, a 0/1 flag
read as a count gets summed. `r_data_types()` classifies each column by role and
returns the dataset with columns coerced to the inferred type, so character IDs
become factors and 0/1 indicators become logical. Read that sentence twice: it
returns the *coerced data*, not a report about it. To see what changed, compare
the source class against the inferred class yourself.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
typed <- r_data_types(dat)
data.frame(
  variable = names(dat),
  source   = vapply(dat,   \(x) class(x)[1], character(1)),
  inferred = vapply(typed, \(x) class(x)[1], character(1)),
  row.names = NULL
) |>
  subset(source != inferred) |>
  gt() |>
  tab_header(title = "Columns retyped by r_data_types()")
